  "doc_id": "44707",
  "text": "A potential worry is the claim by Distler and Nelson [CITATION_1] that the bosonic (2, 1) model (with the ξη system) does not correctly reproduce the topological gravity results, and that the full BRST machinery is necessary to obtain the correct measure of integration over the moduli space. It is quite difficult to compute topological gravity amplitudes from first principles using standard worldsheet methods, in any of the fieldtheoretic formulations. The difficulty stems from the very nature of the observables: amplitudes are naively zero before integration over the moduli space, and receive contributions only from \"contact terms\" (degenerations of the punctured surface). This is related to the fact that there are no non-trivial closed string states in the absolute BRST cohomology, the only observables being in the semi-relative cohomology.",
